english:
  title: A Dialogue on the Arrangement of Formations
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    One inquired of me: "The formations described by the Masters Ikjae, Sambong, and Haojing differ in certain respects from those arranged in recent times. What are these differences in detail?"

    I replied: "What Sambong described were merely the outlines of formation practice; he did not venture into detailed explanation. As for Haojing's work, though it occasionally differs from present formations, its essential meaning simply follows what Ikjae set forth."

    He then asked: "Sambong speaks of 'the front rank remaining still, the rear guard rushing forth to draw out the enemy.' Many critics dispute this, and neither Ikjae nor Haojing made this assertion. Why do you alone follow it?"

    I answered: "The art of formation originates with the Yellow Emperor and was perfected in the Zhou dynasty. Investigating its fundamental intent, we find it aims at invincibility. The ancients rightly said that Zhou's system was intricate yet deeply refined. When Sambong speaks of the front rank with its center axis standing firm as the defensive force, the rear guard advancing first to draw the enemy as the main force, and the left and right wings striking from the flanks as the irregular force—such a scheme of mutual reinforcement is so complete that it seems to capture the true principle the ancients understood in creating formations, surpassing what other theorists have grasped."

    "Yet," he objected, "while Sambong's principle of self-fortification is sound, military strategy requires deep foresight. If we follow this method, how do we respond when the enemy strikes from behind? Moreover, our realm has little flat terrain and much rough ground. When meeting the enemy, can we truly deploy the rear guard to advance first? Even on flat ground, with a million soldiers arrayed, the distance between front and rear ranks is considerable. When the enemy engages us, must we not wait for the rear guard to advance? Is this not dangerously slow? The critics are not entirely wrong. Upon what do you base your certainty in following Sambong?"

    I responded: "The principle of the rear guard advancing to draw the enemy applies when the foe appears to the front—this is single-front warfare. Should the enemy appear both front and rear, this is multi-front combat, and such circumstances have their own methods. For three-front or four-front engagement, each has its proper tactics. How can one judge single-front warfare by the rules of multi-front battle? Moreover, scouts and cavalry patrol outward—some ranging a hundred li, others two hundred. How could they not detect an enemy threatening from behind? With scouts already in place, even if front and rear positions are distant, there is no danger of the rear guard advancing too slowly. Should enemies suddenly appear, does not the point of contact itself become the front? As for rough terrain, there are specific formations for such conditions—mountain formations, valley warfare, water combat, and the like. Consider the five elemental correspondences: left is azure dragon, right is white tiger, front is vermillion phoenix, rear is black tortoise—these are consistent throughout heaven and earth, past and present. The enemy advances with a sharp formation, while we meet them with a curved formation, which accords with water overcoming fire. The principle of the rear guard advancing first derives from the fundamental law of the five formations. The ancients established these methods with clear purpose; we cannot dismiss them lightly."

    "Yet," he countered, "while the rear guard's advance ensures self-preservation, the water-overcomes-fire doctrine clings to the strange and baseless teachings of the five elements. Are you unaware of Mencius, who said heaven's timing matters less than terrain's advantage, or of Tang Taizong, who warned that adhering to taboos loses sight of actual circumstances?"

    "How easily you speak," I replied. "In discussing methods and matters, one must not lean to extremes. To rigidly bind oneself to the five elements is wrong, yet to abandon them entirely is equally wrong. Is there anything under heaven that exists outside the five elements? Consider formation practice alone: are not the five directions—left, right, front, rear, and center—the positions of the five elements? Are not azure, yellow, red, white, and black the colors of the five elements? Are not curved, straight, sharp, round, and square the shapes of the five elements? When enemies deploy straight formations, we counter with square ones; when they use sharp formations, we employ curved ones. Military treatises abound with such examples, all drawing upon the principles of how the five elements generate and overcome one another. Can these be discarded? In the Han dynasty, one hundred eighty-two military treatises were evaluated and condensed to fifty-three, divided into four categories: strategy, formation, yin-yang, and technique. Sixteen works were selected from the yin-yang category alone. Would this have been done without reason?

    "What Mencius and Taizong spoke were words suited to their times. Mencius observed that the world valued heaven's timing and terrain's advantage while neglecting the harmony of people. He therefore weighed these three factors accordingly—much as Confucius, when discussing the three essentials of warfare, military supplies, and trust, prioritized their abandonment in due order. In truth, when one secures the people's harmony, holds the terrain's strength, and encounters favorable timing, none can stand against them. Taizong spoke because generals had lost sight of actual circumstances through excessive adherence to yin-yang taboos. When Taizong asked whether such arts could be dispensed with, General Li Jing replied they could not. He then expounded on what lies deepest in military strategy: the Dao, heaven and earth, and the general's virtue. Taizong affirmed this. By 'heaven and earth' is meant heaven's timing and terrain's advantage."

    He then asked: "You follow the principle of the rear guard advancing first, yet you also speak of the point of contact becoming the front. Do you not blend the teachings of Ikjae and Haojing? Why is your position inconsistent and uncommitted?"

    "The rear guard advancing is the constant method of meeting the enemy," I explained. "The point of contact becoming the front is adaptive response when suddenly encountering the foe. To know only constancy while remaining ignorant of adaptive tactics is flawed; to pursue only adaptation while ignoring the ancients' fundamental principles of formation is equally flawed. When combined, these constitute proper balance. Where is the inconsistency?"

    "You prize Sambong's teaching as capturing the ancients' fundamental intent," he pressed, "yet his writings state 'the signal-staffs number five as the flags number five.' The recent formations also transmit this, yet you reject it and employ flags solely for signaling. Why?"

    "The designs of signal-staffs and flags differ slightly but serve the same purpose," I explained. "However, each of the five commands bears its color, each command-division has five sections, and each section has its flags. With flags so numerous, they dazzle the troops' eyes. Add to this that signal-staffs are similarly colored, creating great confusion such that soldiers mistake flags for signal-staffs. Ikjae and Haojing's arrangements serve the troops' familiarity and cannot be altered."

    "Ikjae, Sambong, and Haojing all designated the four directions as 'commands,' yet the recent formations change 'command' to 'wing,'" he observed. "You accept neither and substitute 'guard' instead. Is there a principle behind this?"

    "There is no deep meaning," I replied. "The three masters, following earlier texts, used 'command.' The recent formations, to avoid imitating the upper kingdom's five-command system, necessitate this change. Furthermore, 'wing' derives from birds and applies only to left and right; applying it to front, rear, and center seems improper. Thus I substituted 'guard.'"

    "In the three-formation method," he continued, "some arrange the left-front and right-rear as separate formations, while others pair the left-rear with the right-front. You choose the left-front pairing. Why?"

    "In military formations, the rule of turning is rightward," I answered. "In straight advance, the right proceeds forward while the left falls back. In the three-formation arrangement, the front retreats leftward while the rear advances rightward—the principle is identical. Whether turning formations or meeting the enemy, all turns must be rightward. This law cannot be disturbed."

    "Does formation and response exhaust all tactical principles?" he asked.

    "No," I said. "The three armies must have their eyes trained to recognize flag colors, their ears to distinguish drum and horn calls, their hands skilled in weapons, their feet practiced in the pace and tempo of advance, and their minds knowing both the severity of punishment and the benefit of reward. The drill-master's methods must be thoroughly taught. Only then, adapting form to terrain and response to circumstance, will formations stand firm and battles be won unfailingly. How can one cling rigidly to fixed methods?"

    "Why did Confucius claim not to have studied military arrangements, and why did Mencius call them a grave offense?" he asked.

    "These were words spoken in righteous indignation," I replied. "Duke Ling of Wei was an unvirtuous lord who, upon meeting the sage, inquired about formations—revealing his inclination toward warfare. Thus Confucius claimed ignorance and departed without answering. In Mencius' time, the realm was consumed by warfare—contending for cities and lands, slaughtering until corpses filled the fields and the common people's suffering was extreme. Mencius therefore said that those skilled in warfare merit capital punishment and forming skilled formations constitutes grave crime—words meant to remedy the crisis of his age. Scholars must approach the sage's words with open hearts, carefully discerning their meaning, not seizing upon a single utterance as definitive truth.

    "The Sima Fa states: 'Though all-under-heaven be peaceful, forgetting warfare brings danger; though a realm be great, loving warfare brings ruin.' The Hu commentary says: 'Military affairs should not be loved—to love them invites calamity from one's own hand. Yet they cannot be despised—to despise them invites the calamities others inflict.' Such teachings avoid extremes and maintain proper balance. The Zhou Duke's instruction to King Cheng was 'govern your forces well,' while the Duke of Shao warned King Kang to 'deploy the six armies broadly.' Taking the Zhou Duke's great teachings, comparing them with Confucius and Mencius' sage wisdom, and examining both the Sima Fa and Hu commentary, one grasps the ancients' true intent regarding military affairs."

    Thus have I, Gye-ryang, composed these writings on formations and recorded my deliberations on principles of selection and rejection, humbly presenting them for Your Majesty's examination and judgment.
