    - The five elements—wood, fire, earth, metal, and water—were understood in traditional East Asian thought as fundamental generative and destructive forces governing all phenomena, including military strategy.
    - The five formations refer to the basic tactical configurations employed in traditional East Asian warfare.
    - Mencius' criticism of warfare (in the context of rulers pursuing conquest for personal gain) was distinguished from necessary, just warfare for defense or restoration of order.
